  "prompt": "How long do you have to live on your own (and in poor conditions) to qualify for the Pell Grant? Is the Pell Grant a scholarship for the poor?",
  "response": "The Pell Grant is a federal financial aid program in the United States designed to help low-income students afford college. It is not specifically a scholarship, but rather a grant that does not need to be repaid. Eligibility for the Pell Grant is primarily based on financial need, which is determined by the Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA).\n\nTo qualify as an independent student on the FAFSA\u2014meaning you do not have to report your parents' income\u2014you must meet specific criteria. These criteria include:\n\n1. **Being 24 years old or older by December 31 of the award year**.\n2. **Being married or separated but not divorced**.\n3. **Having dependents (children or other individuals) who receive more than half of their support from you**.\n4. **Being an orphan or ward of the court (or were until age 18)**.\n5. **Being a veteran or active-duty member of the U.S. Armed Forces**.\n6. **Being a graduate or professional student**.\n\nIf you do not meet any of these criteria, you are typically considered a dependent student, and your parents' financial information will be required to determine your eligibility for the Pell Grant.\n\nLiving on your own or in poor conditions does not automatically make you independent unless you meet one of the criteria above. For example, if you are under 24, unmarried, and have no dependents, you would still need to report your parents' income unless you can demonstrate extraordinary circumstances (e.g., abuse, abandonment, or other severe situations) to your financial aid office.\n\n### Is the Pell Grant for the poor?\nYes, the Pell Grant is primarily intended for students with significant financial need. The amount awarded depends on your Expected Family Contribution (EFC), which is calculated based on your FAFSA information, along with other factors like the cost of attendance at your school and your enrollment status. Students with the lowest EFCs typically receive the maximum Pell Grant award, while those with higher EFCs may receive reduced amounts.\n\nIf you have specific questions about your eligibility or need help filling out the FAFSA, it\u2019s a good idea to consult with your school\u2019s financial aid office.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
